# Migrate Hospital Management System from MySQL to MongoDB

## Background

The current HMS backend uses **MySQL** (`mysql2/promise`) with raw SQL queries across 11 controllers, 11 route files, and a seed script. The user wants to switch to **MongoDB**. This plan replaces `mysql2` with `mongoose`, converts all SQL tables to Mongoose models, and rewrites every controller to use Mongoose queries — while keeping all API routes and response shapes identical so the frontend works without changes.

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **MongoDB Connection**: The plan assumes you have MongoDB installed locally or want to use MongoDB Atlas. The default connection string will be `mongodb://localhost:27017/hms_db`. Please confirm if you want to use a different connection.

> [!WARNING]
> **Breaking Change**: The existing MySQL database and seed data will NOT be migrated automatically. After switching, you'll need to run the new MongoDB seed script to populate data. The SQL schema file will be kept for reference.

> [!IMPORTANT]  
> **ID Format Change**: MySQL uses auto-incrementing integer IDs (`1, 2, 3...`). MongoDB uses ObjectId strings (`507f1f77bcf86cd799439011`). The frontend code that references numeric IDs will still work because we pass IDs as route params, but the format of IDs will change.

